<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-855-038  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 855 038.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Nov 6 1989 v6 n44 p105(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How and why of employee crimes. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bequai, August.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EmployeeTheft of FundsTheft of InformationComputer Crimes.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Howy and Why of Employee CrimesandM;Thefts committed by employees, consultants and others in positions of trustare destroying American organizations from within.andP;  The U.S.andP;  Chamber ofCommerce says that unscrupulous insiders contribute to nearly half of allbusiness failures, and security experts places losses from insider crime atmore than $40 billion a year.andP;  With today's networked computer systems, evenan entry-level clerk can steal millions from his or her employer.andM;If insider crime is such a serious problem, why isn't anything being doneabout it?andP;  Well, peer pressure or misguided loyalty often prevents employeesfrom blowing the whistle on the criminal activities of their co-workers.andO;Victimized companies tend not to report insider crimes to the police becausethey fear adverse publicity.andP;  So, insiders know they're generally safe fromprosecution.andM;It's up to organizations, then, to take the initiative in plugging insidercrime at the source.andP;  Before an organization can implement an internalcrime-prevention program, however, its management must understand how and whyemployees criminals do what they do.andM;Headline-making employee crimes may involve selling or misusing proprietarydata, selling customer lists to competitors, or taking advantage of insideinformation, such as merger or acquisition plans, to make a killing in thestock market.andP;  But most employee thefts are small-potatoes crimes, oftencarried out over long periods.andM;Here are some of the tactics insiders use to defraud organizations: doctoringtime sheets; padding expense accounts and submitting false expense vouchers;setting up &quot;ghost employee&quot; schemes (a consultant may invoice a company forservices provided by a non-existent worker); making or authorizing paymentsto non-existent suppliers; arranging to have suppliers paid twice andpocketing the second payment; over-charging customers and pocketing thedifference; doctoring inventory lists; diverting incoming payments orsupplies; using company photocopiers or computers without authorization;pilfering equipment and supplies; and making unauthorized copies of companysoftware.andM;Some dishonest insiders steal for personal gain, but many others don't.andO;Non-financial motives for crimes against employers include revenge for aperceived wrong, hatred of the organization or industry, pressure byco-workers and outsiders, the challenge of beating the system, pooremployer/employee relations, ideological or political reasons, corruptworkplace environments, and drug or alcohol abuse in the workplace.andO;</TEXT></DOC>